9. Why This Works

keep stores the best subarray ending at the current index without any deletion.

delete stores the best subarray ending at the current index after using exactly one deletion.

When computing delete, there are only two possibilities:

1. Delete the current element and keep the previous valid subarray (keep(previous)).


2. The deletion was already used earlier, so extend the deleted-state subarray (delete + arr[i]).



These transitions consider every valid subarray exactly once, so the algorithm is correct.



---

10. Edge Cases

Single element array.

All elements negative.

Delete the first element.

Delete the last element.

No deletion gives the best answer.

Deleting a positive element is never beneficial.

Maximum answer comes after removing one large negative value.



---

11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> "This is an extension of Kadane's Algorithm. I maintain two DP states while scanning the array once. keep represents the maximum subarray sum ending at the current index without any deletion. delete represents the maximum subarray sum ending here after one deletion has already been used. For each element, keep follows the normal Kadane transition, while delete either deletes the current element or extends a previously deleted subarray. The answer is the maximum value seen in either state. This gives an O(n) time and O(1) space solution."




---

12. Key Takeaways

Extension of Kadane's Algorithm.

Two DP states are sufficient.

No recursion required.

Constant extra space.

Classic example of state transition DP.



---

13. Common Mistakes

Initializing delete to 0 instead of negative infinity.

Forgetting that the remaining subarray must be non-empty.

Updating keep before computing delete (you need the previous keep value).

Returning only keep instead of the maximum of keep and delete.

Mishandling arrays containing all negative numbers.



